post_text:
Nineteen years ago, on September 11, 2001, life across the United States came to a halt. In their cars, their offices, waiting for appointments, or shopping in stores, people of all ethnicities, all religions, and all political affiliations reacted in horror to the attacks on the World Trade Center and Pentagon. We watched as the grim statistics became clear throughout the day: 2,977 people lost their lives.

In the weeks that followed, we saw the nation pull together ‚Äì emergency personnel responding without hesitation, neighbors comforting neighbors, volunteers combing through wreckage, military personnel deploying around the world in efforts to keep our nation safe. Today, as we remember the fallen, please also remember the sense of determination to build a better nation, the kindness, the self-sacrifice, and the compassion built out of the ashes of that fateful day. We will never forget.

#AVUHSD #AVFindYouPath

(This picture was taken at last year's 9/11 ceremony at Knight High School)

Antelope Valley Union High School District uses an electronic flyer communication tool called ‚ÄúPeachjar.‚Äù To view school-approved digital flyers, simply click the Peachjar link on your school‚Äôs website homepage. This ‚Äúgreen‚Äù initiative saves our schools tons of paper and reduce copy costs by thousands of dollars. On top of that, posting school flyers in this "electronic backpack" removes a significant administrative burden from teachers, office staff, and volunteers.

To ensure smooth delivery of this communication, we suggest you add school@peachjar.com (or your district‚Äôs selected ‚Äúfrom email address‚Äù) to your email contacts. When you receive your first eflyer, be sure to click ‚Äúalways display images.‚Äù This system is used exclusively for distribution of school-approved flyers. Your email address will not be shared or used for any other purpose. Thank you for supporting our efforts to ensure parents are well informed about school programs, activities, and events.

Meal service will take place at all eight of our comprehensive high schools Monday through Friday from 11:30 am-1:00 pm. Lunch and a ‚Äúnext day‚Äù breakfast will be distributed.

An authorized parent or guardian may receive up to six meal kits for children who are not present. Please provide a child(ren)‚Äôs identification when receiving more than six meal kits.

Please visit avfood.org for more information or email us at food@avhsd.org with any questions.

post_text:
September is Suicide Prevention Month and the Antelope Valley High School District is on a mission to prevent suicide by reducing the stigma attached to talking about suicide. Over the next month, through Google Classrooms, we will be sharing information, videos, and resources related to suicide awareness and prevention. We encourage you to view these resources with your child, continue the conversation at home, and help break the stigma of silence. Please visit https://teenlineonline.org/parents/suicide for more resources on how to have these challenging conversations and how to better identify warning signs. Suicide is preventable, and we are all key to prevention.

National Suicide Prevention Hotline:
TEXT 741-741 or CALL 800-273-8255

#AVUHSD #AVTake2ToPreventSuicide

Although the current power outages in Antelope Valley have not impacted our ability to provide online instruction at this time, we understand it could impact some students‚Äô ability to access their online classes.

Class materials will continue to be posted online for students who are unable to attend their classes due to any power outages. Students can work directly with their teachers if time or additional accommodations are needed as a result of this power interruption.

Some helpful tips:
-Make sure phones, hotspots, and Chromebooks are fully charged.
-Ensure portable charging devices are also fully charged.
-If you lose power, unplug or turn off appliances, equipment, and electronics to avoid damage caused by surges when the power is restored.

For the latest information regarding power outages in your area, go to the Southern California Edison Outage Map at https://www.sce.com/outage-center/check-outage-status

While the lessening of these restrictions is not to the extent needed to host a traditional graduation ceremony, our school leadership teams are now working diligently to plan car parades to honor our graduates. You will receive information related to your school‚Äôs plans in the coming week.

Our commitment to host traditional graduation ceremonies has not changed with this latest update. We will continue to monitor the ever-changing nature of this health crisis and communicate with you as information becomes available. As previously shared, we will give reasonable advance notice of the scheduled ceremony.

post_text:
The Antelope Valley Union High School District remains committed to our students and will continue to offer summer school. The dates for summer school will be June 29th- July 24th, 2020. Students will continue to be able to earn up to one semester (5) or two semesters (10) of credit within the 19 days, five hours of work per day. Due to the ever-changing landscape caused by the Corona Virus we anticipate that summer school will continue in a distance learning format. We will continue to monitor the guidance and recommendations of state and local officials to determine if and to what extent we can begin to provide on-campus supports for students. Registration information will be available on Monday, May 11 through Friday, May 22, 2020. A link to register can be found on your school‚Äôs website under the ACADEMICS tab, then SUMMER SCHOOL. You will be hearing directly from your school site with more detailed information related to Summer School.

#AVUHSD #AVFindYourPath

post_text:
After considering the input from students, staff, and parents through workgroups, surveys, and community petition, it is overwhelmingly clear that our community desires to postpone our graduation ceremonies to a date when it is safe to gather in person. We support this desire and have postponed all graduation ceremonies to a date to be determined in accordance with the state and local officials. Because of the ever-changing nature of this health crisis, we will not establish a set date and time for the ceremonies to take place; however, we will continue to communicate with you as information becomes available. Families will be given reasonable advance notice of the scheduled ceremony.

Meanwhile, student and staff leaders at each of our schools are preparing a virtual ‚ÄòSenior Celebration‚Äô on the originally scheduled graduation date. These celebrations will provide the opportunity to recognize the sentiment of this date in a unique, fun way. You will receive information specific to your school‚Äôs celebration in the coming weeks.

#AVUHSD #AVFindYourPath

post_text:
The Academies of the Antelope Valley, Virtual Academy students Layali Homod and Vani Tyagi were recently chosen as the state SkillsUSA Officers for California. They were two of twenty high school students selected to serve as SkillsUSA California state officers at the state conference. For the next school year, these individuals will travel to events across the state, sharing the message of Career and Technical Education, and specifically the message of SkillsUSA.

SkillsUSA California officers work together to develop engaging educational conferences for the 45 thousand members statewide. Additionally, they visit business and industry representatives and legislative representatives. Through effective speaking and facilitating techniques, SkillsUSA California leaders communicate the message of career-readiness.

Congrats Layali & Vani! We are so proud of you both.

#AVUHSD #AVFindYourPath

Quartz Hill High School invites you to show your support for our class of 2020 by honking your horn as you drive by our Floyd Nicholson football stadium at 8:20pm Friday night.

We will be turning on the lights at 8:20 (20:20 military time) for 20 minutes. During this window, drive by and give a honk for our seniors!

Keeping in mind the stay-at-home order, please do not stop, do not get out, and please return home after... but lay on that horn as you drive by! If you are supporting seniors, make it a long continuous honk... if you are a senior, make it short blasts. Go Rebs!

Today we spent time with the Senior Class Presidents at each of our schools. They shared bright spots they have found in this time of physical distancing- more moments with their families before they begin their next chapter, time to explore interest and passions that had taken a backseat, and strengthened bonds with teachers and classmates. They represented their classes‚Äô collective desire to have a traditional graduation ceremony and offered creative solutions for other senior events. While the circumstances are less than ideal, this group of leaders are determined to make the most of their moment! We are proud of you 2020!

post_text:
Our decision last week to physically close schools through the end of the academic year, brings with it the cancellation of school activities and events, which includes prom, academic awards, and traditional graduation ceremonies.

We know that this decision weighs heavy on our students, their families, and our staff who all treasure these moments of celebrations and traditions. In light of these cancellations, we are committed to finding alternative ways to honor our students. We‚Äôve included a survey that allows us to hear what events are most important to you and ideas for ways to make them memorable given the current constraints. We are confident that together we will identify creative and innovative ways to make the best of these special moments. Please use this link https://antelopevalley.co1.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_0P01NtAhv6XkfgV to share your input. We look forward to hearing your ideas and working collaboratively to come up with solutions.

#AVUHSD #AVFindYourPath #AVDistanceLearning

This past October our campus supervisors participated in ‚ÄúSTOP THE BLEED TRAINING‚Äù hosted by Antelope Valley Hospital. ‚ÄúStop the Bleed‚Äù is a national campaign launched to encourage bystanders to become trained, equipped and empowered to help in a bleeding emergency before professional help arrives. Stop The Bleed Kits have been distributed to all of our school administration and security offices.

Thanks to the generosity of Antelope Valley Hospital, who matched the District investment, we are able to provide additional kits to all our sites! Their contribution demonstrates the vital participation of community partners working together towards school safety!

If you are interested in becoming training, contact Jeremiah Johns, RN, Trauma Clinical Coordinator, at 661-949-5677 or jeremiah.johns@avhospital.org.

During this week‚Äôs City Council meeting, the City recognized Commissioner Nigel Holly, Bishop Henry Hearns, students of the Antelope Valley Union High School District, and many other community leaders and organizations who committed their time and energy to organize this year‚Äôs Justice Sunday event. In honor of Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. Day, this year‚Äôs play themed ‚ÄòD√©j√† Vu‚Äô captured influential moments throughout African American history, such as the Civil Rights Movement and Black Lives Matter. Every member in the audience could tell that the students worked extremely hard to put together a play that incorporated dancing, singing, historical lessons, and much more. Thank you to everyone involved for organizing yet another successful Justice Sunday event. We are proud that such an amazing program has become an annual tradition in our community.

post_text:
Last week the Wolf Connection visited students at Desert Winds High School.

Wolf Connection is an education and empowerment program with wolfdogs, Youth Ambassadors, as the centerpiece. With the help of these magnificent animals, men and women from all walks of life learn about nature and conservation, work through the challenges in their lives, learn to be of service by responsibly caring for another living being, and work towards becoming the kind of person they want to be.

The District is proud to partner with Wolf Connection in providing this unique opportunity for our students.

Palmdale High School Alumni in action at Arizona State University!

Derek Hagan, PHS Alum and ASU Hall of Fame Inductee, currently serves as a Football Analyst for the Sun Devils. The Sun Devils take on Florida State University in the 2019 Sun Bowl tomorrow afternoon. Tune in to CBS at 11:00 a.m.

Kaelynn Nadonza, Class of 2018, is currently using the skills learned during her time in the PHS Sports Medicine Program serving as the Student Manager for ASU Women's Gymnastics. The Sun Devils open with the defending NCAA Champions - University of Oklahoma - January 11th on ESPNU.

These Falcon Alumni demonstrate that the traits and skills you build as a student athlete can translate into sports-related careers beyond high school. Forks Up!

Students: Apply for 2019-2020 ACM/CSTA Cutler-Bell Prize

The ACM/CSTA Cutler-Bell Prize in High School Computing recognizes talented high school students in computer science. Judges will be looking for submissions that demonstrate ingenuity, complexity, relevancy, originality, and a desire to further computer science as a discipline. The application process involves a Challenge that focuses on having the student develop an artifact that engages modern computing technology and computer science. The application period closes January 12, 2020.

To learn more, visit https://csteachers.org/page/csta-acm-cutler-bell-prize

Celebrating Knight High School AVID tonight!

A KHS parent shared her appreciation for Ms. Powell writing, "My daughter always comes home and says great things about her in how she goes on and beyond for the students and how much she pushes them to be someone in life with a purpose. My daughter has also told me what an influence she has been to her. We need more teachers like her that care about teaching not just collecting a paycheck."

A student shared about Ms. McCall stating, "McCall is a genuinely sweet soul. She is always there when you need advice, guidance, a listening ear, or a mentor. She‚Äôs never judgmental when giving advice and I think that‚Äôs something students need. We don‚Äôt like to feel judged, we liked to feel helped. McCall is an amazing person and a great teacher for many reasons, more than I can count on two hands. She‚Äôs just a joyful person (no pun intended) and I think everyone should strive to be more like her. So full of life, bright with energy, love and care. Thank you McCall, for being you!"

text:
Celebrating Knight High School AVID tonight!

A KHS parent shared her appreciation for Ms. Powell writing, "My daughter always comes home and says great things about her in how she goes on and beyond for the students and how much she pushes them to be someone in life with a purpose. My daughter has also told me what an influence she has been to her. We need more teachers like her that care about teaching not just collecting a paycheck."

A student shared about Ms. McCall stating, "McCall is a genuinely sweet soul. She is always there when you need advice, guidance, a listening ear, or a mentor. She‚Äôs never judgmental when giving advice and I think that‚Äôs something students need. We don‚Äôt like to feel judged, we liked to feel helped. McCall is an amazing person and a great teacher for many reasons, more than I can count on two hands. She‚Äôs just a joyful person (no pun intended) and I think everyone should strive to be more like her. So full of life, bright with energy, love and care. Thank you McCall, for being you!"

#ThankfulforAVUHSD #AVUHSD #AVFindYourPath #KnightHighSchool

Sarah Woods Hadsell, Antelope Valley High School Class of 1998, has published a new children's book called "Pirates Love Pajamas". Sarah shared that her love of writing was fine-tuned during her time at AVHS. She credits her creative writing teacher for instilling in her the belief that she was capable of chasing her dreams of becoming a published author.

post_text:
Attn: Palmdale High School Families

Good morning Falcon Family,

Early this morning we became aware of a social media post warning students to remain at home from school due to a possible threat. This message was immediately reported to all school officials, security personnel and the Los Angeles County Sheriff‚Äôs Department, and an investigation is taking place. While the message did not identify Palmdale High School as being the site receiving a direct threat, we will ensure that we have heightened security throughout campus out of an abundance of caution. Safety and security remain our top priority, and school will remain open today with normal class schedules and activities.

Thank you,

Dr. Robert Harris
Principal

post_text: UPDATE 11/20/19: LASD identified and located the student who made the alleged threat and an arrest was made. Quartz Hill High School will be in open and classes fully in session. All school activities are on as schedule.
shared_text:
Quartz Hill High School
November 19, 2019 at 9:16 PM ¬∑

Dear Quartz Hill High School family,

This afternoon, Quartz Hill High School was made aware of a social media post by one student referencing an alleged threat of another student. The social media post was immediately reported to the Lancaster Sheriff Department and promptly investigated. Both parties have been identified and we will continue to work with our local law enforcement agency.

We appreciate those who reached out, notifying us of the concern, and take this opportunity to remind everyone- If you see something, say something.

He's back! Knight High School Alum, Paul George, debuted with the Clippers this past week. He put up 33 points on Thursday night against the New Orleans Pelicans. Saturday night against the Atlanta Hawks, Paul scored 37 points in less than 21 minutes, setting a new NBA record! Welcome home, Paul!
